(sorry for double comment, hit send on the first one mindlessly)

> Top-level fields in package.json should be respected by all tools that work with packages.

@GeoffreyBooth again, just want to disagree here. Top level pacakge.json is intentionally vague - any tool can "add" fields to it. There are many, many, many examples of this, even between package managers - see overrides vs. resolutions, engines, literally any linting tooling or compiler tools. Functionally, this is not how the ecosystem works.

> The pnpm users are running the wrong version of pnpm problem feels like something that perhaps pnpm could solve on its own.

@GeoffreyBooth I fully agree with this and think this is explictly a non-issue for Node.js.

>That is a great goal, but it doesn't mean that every package manager wants to utilize that solution, and I would like to state that they shouldn't have to.

@MylesBorins huge +1 to this. IMO the Node.js project should not be making decisions that _force_ a package manager to implement something. We should be giving them _options_ that they can take advantage of that will benefit _our_ users DX. This does not seem like "fairness" to me, if "fairness" is a stated goal (which is clearly and reasonably challenged in this issue).

> Forcing all future package managers to support specific features, and making corepack the only blessed path into Node.js core, is not fair.

Again, full +1.

> It feels like a bug to me if Nodes documentation defines a packageManager field and then the package manager that Node includes, npm, doesnt support it. And npm supporting packageManager when installed via Corepack, an installation method that npm doesnt support, doesnt count. It still feels inconsistent and broken.

@GeoffreyBooth Honestly, I agree with this and it captures something that seems to be a struggle in this thread: some folks' perception is that corepack is being built independently and operates outside of the Node.js decision making structure. If that's true, what fields it supports should not be the concern of Node.js. If Corepack _is_ a part of Node.js to the point its docs are shipping inside of the Node.js documentation, IMO that is surface area that Node.js fully owns and Corepack being an independent tool is not a valid way to justify decisions around critique of its DX. Again, this would be much easier to discuss if we strictly outlined the relationship between Node.js and package managers and how Corepack is a part of that.
